Chapter 1: The Silver Shard
​The air in Sector Four tasted like stale copper and ozone.
​Finn held his breath, pressed flat against the damp concrete of a half-collapsed storefront. He was hyper-focused, pouring every ounce of desperate ambition into his command word.
​He whispered the activation sequence—a low, grating sound practiced until his throat was raw. The familiar, useless chill spread across his skin, the phantom sensation of camouflage. For one precious second, his hand flickered, his skin becoming slightly blurry, like heat rising off asphalt.
​Then, just as quickly, the blur snapped back into sharp focus. He was exactly where he started. Exposed. Weak.
​“Time,” a gravelly voice announced.
​Finn flinched, his heart sinking. He didn't even have to turn around to know it was Commander Silas.
​Silas was a mountain of a man, a Sovereign-level presence who didn't need to raise his voice to be heard. His power, Invisible Wall, was the cornerstone of Sector Seven’s survival—a Tier 7 static defense that could withstand the impact of a falling meteor or a Class Five Rupture Lord without him flinching. As he stood there, leaning against a rusted lamp post, the air for ten feet around him was perfectly still, distorted by an oily shimmer that marked a barrier no physical force could penetrate.
​“One point two seconds,” Silas noted, clicking his worn stopwatch. “You’ve successfully made yourself look like a smudge on a dirty lens for long enough to blink. An improvement, I suppose.”
​Finn clenched his fists, the self-contempt tasting like ash. “It’s not useless, it’s limited,” Finn insisted, trying to regain his composure.
​Silas stepped into the dusty light, his Tier 7 pressure making the gravity in the street feel twice as heavy. “In this world, Finn, power is currency. And yours is a joke. You’ve been in Field Salvage for two years. Most hunters your age are already Tiers 3 or 4, leading squads. You’re still picking through garbage. Focus on being smart. It’s the only way a fly like you survives the Rupture.”
​Silas gestured toward the center of the street, where the "real" Hunters had just finished a pack of Kinetic Vipers. The monsters lay still—sleek, grey-armored predators known for blistering speed.
​“Get to work,” Silas ordered. “Retrieve the primary cores and clear the street.”
​The Battlefield
​Finn walked onto the street alone. The static energy from the fight made the hairs on his arms stand up. The elite hunters had already moved on, leaving the "body-bag filler" to do the dirty work.
​He approached the largest Viper. Using a specialized Guild tool, he pried open the creature's chest plate. The primary Kinetic Shard—a pulsing blue crystal—sat in the center. He scooped it into his official containment pouch, but his eyes caught a flicker deeper in the wound.
​Hidden behind a jagged, internal rib was a small, needle-like Silver Shard.
​It was a freak occurrence—a rare anomaly that the high-tier hunters had somehow missed during the heat of battle. A secondary shard of this purity appearing in a Class One monster was a chance in a million.
​Finn leaned closer, a sudden, magnetic curiosity pulling at him. He didn't know why, but he felt an undeniable attraction to the shard’s humming energy. It felt like a promise of something more than "Shimmering Hide." Driven by a sudden impulse, Finn reached past the slime and the bone. His fingers closed around the silver sliver.
​The Inheritance
​The jolt was white-hot.
​The silver crystal didn't just feel fast; it felt like a compressed storm. It dissolved instantly into his palm, sinking into his skin like liquid ink. Finn gasped, biting his lip hard enough to draw blood to keep from screaming.
​For a terrifying second, he wasn't Finn. He was the Viper—a creature of pure instinct, a blur of grey light moving through the ruins. Then, the vision snapped away.
​A cold, sharp voice echoed in the very center of his mind, completely separate from his own thoughts.
​Inheritance complete. Ability unlocked: Super Speed (Silver).
​Finn stared at his hand. It looked normal, but it felt... electric.
​He looked at a pile of rubble twenty feet away. He focused on the silver energy coiled in his legs. He took one step.
​The world warped.
​The street blurred into a smear of grey and brown. Before he could even draw a full breath, he was standing in front of the rubble. He had crossed twenty feet in a heartbeat.
​It was Tier 2 speed. Not enough to outrun a high-tier veteran, but more than enough to make a mockery of his previous life. His old power, Shimmering Hide, was still there, but it felt like a toy compared to this. He had two powers now. His useless parlor trick, and a stolen, monstrous engine.
​The Report
​Finn wiped the sweat from his brow and quickly finished the salvage. He ensured no trace of his discovery remained in the Viper’s carcass.
​Ten minutes later, he walked into Silas’s office at the Guild Compound. Silas was scanning a data-slate, his Tier 7 presence acting as a silent, crushing weight that filled every corner of the room.
​“Report, Provisional Finn,” Silas commanded without looking up.
​Finn placed the containment pouch on the desk. “Field Salvage complete, Commander. Primary cores secured. Perimeter clear.”
​Silas scanned the pouch, then looked at Finn. His eyes, sharp enough to see through lead plating, searched Finn’s face, lingering on the subtle, new tension in the boy’s shoulders.
​“You’re sweating, Finn. And you're late by three minutes.” Silas leaned forward, the air itself tightening as his Invisible Wall expanded by a fraction. “Did you run into trouble?”
​“Just... moved as fast as I could, sir,” Finn lied, forcing a humble, tired smile. “Shimmering Hide takes a lot out of me.”
​Silas studied him for a long moment, then grunted. “Good. The city needs those shards. Next time, move faster. Ambition doesn't mean anything if you can't keep pace.”
​Finn nodded, his heart hammering against his ribs. I will, he thought, his hand subtly twitching with the ghost of the silver storm. Much, much faster.
​He walked out of the office, leaving the strongest man in the sector—and the most dangerous secret in the city—behind him.
